from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]},{"name":"Jehanne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and Norwegian feminine form of   Johan ."],"variants":[{"name":"Joanne","meanings":["From Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, and so a doublet of   Joan .  This too was revived as a given name in its own right in the first half of the 20th century. It has to some extent been influenced by the independently formed combination <i>Jo Anne</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilde Jehanne d'Airaines was born in 1140, her father, Gauthier II D'AIRAINES-DE DOMART, was 22 and her mother, Louise DE CAYEUX-DE CRESECQUES, was 16. She married Ecuyer Simon d'Ailly in 1155. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1189, in Ailly-le-Haut-Clocher, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1140–1189":"1140–1189","1141–1189":"1141–1189","1142–1207":"1142–1207","1144–1163":"1144–1163","1145–1202":"1145–1202","–1160":"–1160","1130–1181":"1130–1181","1160–1226":"1160–1226","1118–1179":"1118–1179","1124–1182":"1124–1182","1142":"1142","1130":"1130","1163":"1163","1141":"1141","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1182"